      list-style: none;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <main>
    <h1>GOV.UK Need API</h1>

    <p>The Need API stores and provides details about user needs which may or may not be met by GOV.UK.</p>

    <h2>API Information</h2>

    <dl>
      <dt>Formats</dt>
      <dd>JSON</dd>
      <dt>Data access</dt>
      <dd>Read and write</dd>
      <dt>Authentication</dt>
      <dd>Required for all requests.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h2>Endpoints</h2>

    <dl>
      <dt><code>GET /needs</code></dt>
      <dd>Basic information about all user needs in the API. Can be filtered by an <code>organisation_id</code> value.</dd>

      <dt><code>POST /needs</code></dt>
      <dd>Create a new need in the API. Returns a <code>HTTP 201</code> when successful.</dd>

      <dt><code>GET /needs/<em>&lt;need id&gt;</em></code></dt>
      <dd>Complete information about a single need, including history of most recent changes.</dd>

      <dt><code>PUT /needs/<em>&lt;need id&gt;</em></code></dt>
      <dd>Update an existing need in the API. Only provided attributes will be updated.</dd>

      <dt><code>GET /organisations</code></dt>
      <dd>Basic information about all organisations in the API.</dd>

      <dt><code>GET /healthcheck</code></dt>
      <dd>Returns a <code>HTTP 200</code> with the body <code>OK</code>. Used for Nagios health checks.</dd>
    </dl>
  </main>

</body>
